hint_pt:"O califado da era de ouro centrado em Bagdá que preservou o conhecimento antigo",
facts:[
  "The Abbasid Caliphate (750–1258 CE) moved the capital from Damascus to the newly-built city of Baghdad, which became the largest city in the world by 900 CE with over one million inhabitants. The Abbasid period overlapped with the Islamic Golden Age: scholars at the House of Wisdom translated and preserved Greek, Persian and Indian texts, and made original advances in algebra, optics, medicine and astronomy.",
  "The caliphate was destroyed in 1258 CE when the Mongols under Hulagu Khan sacked Baghdad — one of the most catastrophic events in Islamic history. Eyewitnesses reported the Tigris River ran black with ink from burned books and red with blood. The Abbasid cultural legacy, however, survived: much of what Europe called its 'Renaissance' was built on knowledge preserved in Baghdad."
],
